 Repository**\n - Click the \"Fork\" button on GitHub\n - Clone your fork locally\n\n2. **Clone Your Fork**\n ```bash\n git clone https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/marketsage.git\n cd marketsage\n ```\n\n3. **Add Upstream Remote**\n ```bash\n git remote add upstream https://github.com/ORIGINAL_OWNER/marketsage.git\n ```\n\n4. **Install Dependencies**\n ```bash\n npm install\n ```\n\n5. **Set Up Environment Variables**\n ```bash\n cp .env.example .env.local\n # Add your GOOGLE_GENAI_API_KEY\n ```\n\n6. **Run Development Server**\n ```bash\n npm run dev\n ```\n\n---\n\n## Development Setup\n\n### Environment Variables\n\nCreate a `.env.local` file:\n\n```env\n# Required\nGOOGLE_GENAI_API_KEY=your_api_key_here\n\n# Optional (for future features)\n# DATABASE_URL=\n# NEXTAUTH_SECRET=\n# NEXTAUTH_URL=\n```\n\n### Available Scripts\n\n```bash\n# Development server (port 9002)\nnpm run dev\n\n# Genkit development UI\nnpm run genkit:dev\n\n# Genkit with hot reload\nnpm run genkit:watch\n\n# Production build\nnpm run build\n\n# Start production server\nnpm run start\n\n# Lint code\nnpm run lint\n\n# Type checking\nnpm run typecheck\n```\n\n### IDE Setup\n\n**Recommended VSCode Extensions:**\n- ESLint\n- Prettier\n- Tailwind CSS IntelliSense\n- TypeScript and JavaScript Language Features\n\n**VSCode Settings:**\n```json\n{\n \"editor.formatOnSave\": true,\n \"editor.codeActionsOnSave\": {\n \"source.fixAll.eslint\": true\n },\n \"typescript.tsdk\": \"node_modules/typescript/lib\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Project Structure\n\n```\nMarketSage/\n├── src/\n│ ├── ai/ # AI flows and Genkit configuration\n│ ├── app/ # Next.js App Router (pages, layouts, actions)\n│ ├── components/ # React components\n│ ├── hooks/ # Custom React hooks\n│ └── lib/ # Utilities and helpers\n├── public/ # Static assets\n├── tests/ # Test files (future)\n├── docs/ # Additional documentation (future)\n└── config files # Configuration files\n```\n\n---\n\n## How to Contribute\n\n### 1. Find or Create an Issue\n\n- Check [existing issues](https://github.com/owner/marketsage/issues)\n- Comment on an issue to claim it\n- Create a new issue if needed (use templates)\n- Wait for approval before starting work\n\n### 2. Create a Feature Branch\n\n```bash\n# Update your local main branch\ngit checkout main\ngit pull upstream main\n\n# Create a feature branch\ngit checkout -b feature/your-feature-name\n# or\ngit checkout -b fix/bug-description\n```\n\n**Branch Naming Convention:**\n- `feature/` - New features\n- `fix/` - Bug fixes\n- `docs/` - Documentation changes\n- `refactor/` - Code refactoring\n- `test/` - Adding tests\n- `chore/` - Maintenance tasks\n\n### 3. Make Your Changes\n\n- Write clean, maintainable code\n- Follow the coding standards\n- Add comments for complex logic\n- Update documentation if needed\n- Add tests for new features\n\n### 4. Test Your Changes\n\n```bash\n# Run linter\nnpm run lint\n\n# Type checking\nnpm run typecheck\n\n# Test locally\nnpm run dev\nnpm run build\n```\n\n### 5. Commit Your Changes\n\n```bash\ngit add .\ngit commit -m \"feat: add new portfolio sorting feature\"\n```\n\nSee [Commit Guidelines](#commit-guidelines) for format details.\n\n### 6. Push to Your Fork\n\n```bash\ngit push origin feature/your-feature-name\n```\n\n### 7. Create a Pull Request\n\n- Go to your fork on GitHub\n- Click \"New Pull Request\"\n- Fill out the PR template\n- Link related issues\n- Request reviews\n\n---\n\n## Coding Standards\n\n### TypeScript\n\n**Use TypeScript for All Code:**\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good - Explicit types\nfunction calculateTotal(prices: number[]): number {\n return prices.reduce((sum, price) => sum + price, 0);\n}\n\n// ❌ Bad - Using any\nfunction calculateTotal(prices: any): any {\n return prices.reduce((sum, price) => sum + price, 0);\n}\n```\n\n**Use Interfaces and Types:**\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good - Clear type definitions\ninterface Portfolio {\n stocks: Stock[];\n cash: number;\n totalValue: number;\n}\n\ntype Stock = {\n ticker: string;\n shares: number;\n price: number;\n};\n```\n\n### React Components\n\n**Use Functional Components:**\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good - Functional component with types\ninterface ButtonProps {\n label: string;\n onClick: () => void;\n disabled?: boolean;\n}\n\nexport function Button({ label, onClick, disabled }: ButtonProps) {\n return (\n <button onClick={onClick} disabled={disabled}>\n {label}\n </button>\n );\n}\n```\n\n**Component File Structure:**\n```typescript\n// 1. Imports\nimport { useState } from 'react';\nimport { Button } from '@/components/ui/button';\n\n// 2. Types/Interfaces\ninterface ComponentProps {\n // ...\n}\n\n// 3. Component\nexport function Component({ ...props }: ComponentProps) {\n // 4. Hooks\n const [state, setState] = useState();\n \n // 5. Event handlers\n const handleClick = () => {\n // ...\n };\n \n // 6. Render\n return (\n // JSX\n );\n}\n\n// 7. Default export (if needed)\nexport default Component;\n```\n\n### CSS & Styling\n\n**Use Tailwind Classes:**\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good - Tailwind utility classes\n<div className=\"flex items-center gap-4 p-4 bg-white rounded-lg shadow\">\n Content\n</div>\n\n// ❌ Bad - Inline styles\n<div style={{ display: 'flex', padding: '16px', background: 'white' }}>\n Content\n</div>\n```\n\n**Use cn() for Conditional Classes:**\n```typescript\nimport { cn } from '@/lib/utils';\n\n<Button className={cn(\n \"base-styles\",\n isActive && \"active-styles\",\n variant === \"primary\" && \"primary-styles\"\n)} />\n```\n\n### Naming Conventions\n\n**Variables & Functions:**\n- `camelCase` for variables and functions\n- Descriptive names (avoid abbreviations)\n- Boolean variables start with `is`, `has`, `should`\n\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good\nconst isLoading = true;\nconst hasError = false;\nconst shouldShowModal = true;\nconst userPortfolio = getPortfolio();\n\n// ❌ Bad\nconst loading = true;\nconst err = false;\nconst show = true;\nconst data = getPortfolio();\n```\n\n**Components:**\n- `PascalCase` for React components\n- Descriptive names\n\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good\nfunction PortfolioAnalysisCard() { ... }\n\n// ❌ Bad\nfunction portfolioCard() { ... }\n```\n\n**Files:**\n- `PascalCase` for component files\n- `kebab-case` for utility files\n- `camelCase` for TypeScript files\n\n```\ncomponents/PortfolioForm.tsx ✅\nlib/market-data.ts ✅\nai/genkit.ts ✅\n```\n\n### Code Organization\n\n**Keep Functions Small:**\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good - Single responsibility\nfunction calculateTotalValue(stocks: Stock[]): number {\n return stocks.reduce((sum, stock) => sum + stock.value, 0);\n}\n\nfunction formatCurrency(amount: number): string {\n return `₹${amount.toLocaleString('en-IN')}`;\n}\n\n// ❌ Bad - Doing too much\nfunction processPortfolio(stocks: Stock[]): string {\n const total = stocks.reduce((sum, stock) => sum + stock.value, 0);\n return `₹${total.toLocaleString('en-IN')}`;\n}\n```\n\n**Extract Complex Logic:**\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good - Extracted to separate function\nfunction PortfolioForm() {\n const validation = usePortfolioValidation();\n \n return (\n // Simple JSX\n );\n}\n\nfunction usePortfolioValidation() {\n // Complex validation logic\n}\n```\n\n### Comments & Documentation\n\n**JSDoc for Functions:**\n```typescript\n/**\n * Calculates the total portfolio value including cash.\n * \n * @param stocks - Array of stock holdings\n * @param cash - Available cash balance\n * @returns Total portfolio value in rupees\n * \n * @example\n * const total = calculatePortfolioValue(stocks, 50000);\n */\nexport function calculatePortfolioValue(\n stocks: Stock[], \n cash: number\n): number {\n const stockValue = stocks.reduce((sum, s) => sum + s.value, 0);\n return stockValue + cash;\n}\n```\n\n**Inline Comments:**\n```typescript\n// ✅ Good - Explains why, not what\n// Calculate percentage using floor division to avoid floating point errors\nconst percentage = Math.floor((value / total) * 100);\n\n// ❌ Bad - States the obvious\n// Add 1 to count\ncount = count + 1;\n```\n